 Religious Studies, McGill University, reflects the recent renewed interest in Italian reform. Entitled "The Cultural Impact of Italian Reformers," its aim was to gather Vermigli scholars along with Renaissance and Reformation scholars. Half the essays (by Paul Grendler, Cesare Vasoli, Rita Belladonna, Anthony Santosuosso, and Antonio D'Andrea) deal with the general question of Renaissance and Reformation interaction: How are humanism and scholasticism related? Marvin Anderson, Philip McNair, J. Patrick Donnelly, Robert Kingdon, and Joseph C. McLelland focus on the thought and activity of Vermigli himself. Students of theology, history, and philosophy, and specifically of the Renaissance and the Reformation, will welcome this book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCalvinismxCongressesxHistoryx16th centuryxItaly. 0aCalvinismzItalyxCongressesxHistoryy16th century. 0aCalvinismexCongrèsxHistoirex16e sièclexItalie. 0aCalvinismexCongrèsxHistoirex16e sièclexItalie. 0aReformationxCongressesxItaly. 0aReformationzItalyvCongresses. 0aRéforme (Christianisme)xCongrèsxItaliezItaly. 0aRéforme (Christianisme)xCongrèsxItaliexItaly. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Marvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelladonna, Rita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD\x27Andrea, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonnelly, SJ., John Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrendler, Paul F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKingdon, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLelland, Joseph C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.